          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a smooth and proper algebraic variety, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> a smooth divisor in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> be the inclusion of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U=X\setminus  Y]]></fr:tex> into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    We have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i j_*\mathbb {Z}=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\neq 0,1]]></fr:tex>, and the Leray spectral sequence for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> can be identified with the long exact sequence of cohomology

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>451</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>9.2.1.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \ldots          \to  \operatorname {H}_Y^n(X)         \to  \operatorname {H}^n(X)         \to  \operatorname {H}^n(U)         \xrightarrow {\partial } \ldots        \tag{9.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    with
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}_Y^n(X)       = \operatorname {H}^{n-2}(Y,\operatorname {\mathscr {H}}_Y^2).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a reason that was made clear in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.9" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.9.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="3.1.9" />, we identify <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {\mathscr {H}}_Y^2]]></fr:tex> with the constant sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(-1)_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.
    Since the Leray spectral sequence for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> converges, by definition, to the mixed Hodge structure of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(U)]]></fr:tex>, we find that the exact sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>452</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>9.2.1.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \ldots          \to  \operatorname {H}^{n-2}(Y,\mathbb {Z})(-1)         \to  \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Z})         \to \operatorname {H}^n(U,\mathbb {Z})         \xrightarrow {\partial } \ldots        \tag{9.2.1.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is an exact sequence of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The Leray spectral sequence for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> is also the spectral sequence of the filtered complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Omega _X^\bullet (\log  Y),W)]]></fr:tex>;
    the exact sequence above can thus also be identified with that induced by the short exact sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>453</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.3.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>9.2.1.3</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         0         \to  \Omega _X^\bullet          \to  \Omega _X^\bullet (\log  Y)         \xrightarrow {\operatorname {Res}} \Omega _Y^\bullet          \to  0.       \tag{9.2.1.3}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    For this reason, the homomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\partial ]]></fr:tex> in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="9.2.1.2" /> is also called the <fr:em>residue operator</fr:em>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
